Bmvom: entering upon a detailed discussion concerning the dis- puted authorship of the DialogUS, a brief historical outline of the various phases through which the controversy, now more than 300 years old, has passed, will be appropriate.l

The first to-cast any doubt upon the authenticity of our treatise was Beatus Rhenanus (Bilde von Rheinau 1485-1547), in a short 1101·,62 to his edition of the works of Tacitus published in Basle in 1519.

Naturally no attention was paid to objections based upon incred- ibly slender grounds, and scholars continued to regard the Dialogus as Tacitean, until the appearance of Lipsius' famous edition, pub- lished for the first time in 1574. After pointing out some palpable differences between the style of the Dialogus and the other works of the historian, Lipsius concluded as follows: ‘Superest ut de scriptore huius libri verbo admoneam3 quem Tacitum uon esse tam certum apud me est quam si Apollo respondisset. Inclino ut Quintiliano tribuam.² True to this conviction, he issued the Dialogus under Quintilian's name (Fabii Quintiliani ut videtur dialogus an sui saeculi oratores antiquis et quare concedant, Cor- nelio Tacito falso inscriptus).
